<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Decline-Push-Up">Decline Push-Up</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/decline-push-up" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">decline push-up</a> is great for increasing upper chest muscle mass. The primary mover is the pectoralis major. The secondary movers are the deltoids, triceps, rectus abdominis, and obliques.</p>



<p>The decline push-up requires us to place our feet on a chair and hands on the floor. As we lower our chest toward the floor, there is greater emphasis on the pectoralis major clavicular fibers. This is the upper part of the pectoralis major muscle.</p>



<p>This is because the decline position resembles the angle of an incline bench press. An incline of <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7579505/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">30 degrees</a> results in greater activation of the upper portion of the pectoralis major. This highlights its involvement during the decline push-ups.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Chair Decline Push-Ups" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/980233682?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write; encrypted-media"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Decline Push-Up Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Kneel on the floor with your back facing the chair.</li>



<li>Lean forward and place your palms flat on the floor.</li>



<li>Lift both of your legs and place your feet on the chair.</li>



<li>Your weight should now be resting on your palms and the balls of your feet.</li>



<li>Take a deep breath in and brace your core muscles.</li>



<li>Allow your elbows to bend and lower your chest toward the floor&nbsp;</li>



<li>Lower until your upper arm is parallel to the floor.</li>



<li>Exhale and press yourself back up to the starting position.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Place the back of the chair against a wall or hard surface. This will increase stability and prevent it from moving during your set.</li>



<li>Ensure that your hands are at the same level as your shoulders. This will help create a solid base and improve your pressing ability.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



